These items deal with ways youve been
coping with stress resulting
from upsetting events or thoughts related to the recent birth of your child. There are many ways to
try to deal with problems, and these items specifically ask what youve been
doing to cope with stress related to this topic.  Of course, different people deal with things
in different ways, but were interested in how YOU have tried to deal with this
stress.

 

Each item below says something about a
particular way of coping.  We want to
know to what extent (how much or how frequently) youve been doing what each
item says.  Try to respond to each item
separately in your mind from the others.  Also, dont answer on the basis of whether it
seems to be working or not  just whether or not youre doing it. There are no right
or wrong answers, so choose the most accurate answer for YOU  not what you
think most people would say or do.  Make
your answers as true FOR YOU and how you cope with stress resulting from upsetting events or thoughts
related to your pregnancy/ your partners pregnancy, or expecting the birth of
your child as you can. - I turn to work or other activities to take my mind off things.

I planned to take 4 months, but took an extra month. I exhausted my vacation and sick time, then had to take unpaid leave (my employer, the federal government, does not have paid maternity leave). I also purchased private short-term disability insurance, since I could not get state disability (since I am a federal employee).
I took two weeks vacation.  I was aware of benefits provided by the State by chose not to take them. Ideally, I would have stayed home or taken more time as needed in subseqent weeks.
I wish I could have taken more time and had a better source of income/support during maternity leave. As a freelancer it was financially a very stressful time
I wish I had taken off much more, ideally 3 or 4 months, to settle into parenthood
in my personal opinion it is a moment that a father should not miss from his life
I originally was given roughly 6 weeks of paternity leave but I had to put in my paperwork and choose my dates before the baby. But by the time the baby was born I only had about 3 or 4 weeks left.
My company offered 6 weeks for paternity leave and I wished I had more time off.

I don't like to be apart from my baby, I feel that my baby still needs me and not ready to be apart. I am tired and not so energetic while caring for my baby. On my first day of work. I feel so relaxed, so free and comfortable of not having to take care of my baby.

I'm so grateful that I was able to be home with my baby her entire first year. It's so important to us. I want to be with her through her very important developmental years. I'd rather not leave her with a caregiver.

I own my own company and thought I'd be able to go right back because I had put a nursery in my office. Wrong!  I let all my projects taper off and had envisioned going back and getting plenty of work in.  Not even close. At one year I am only just able to sit in front of a computer again.  My company basically went into hibernation and I didn't make any money for our family during that time. It was a big sacrifice but I am so happy I did not have to compromise even a moment with this sweet baby.

I have been able to sorta kinda balance my work schedule to have quality time with the baby and we have been taking him to work which is great because were close =but often hard to get quality work done.  So we continue to compromise on how to manage.

column537: I don't have a fit bit. I dont know

column44: I graduated from UCLA, then spent the time from when I graduated to when I started work to take care of the baby.
I eventually resigned from my position in order to stay at home with our baby
I probably should have taken more time off.

this actually has to do with the cigarette question on the previous page, for which the prompts only accept numerical answers. i was a social smoker, smoking at parties and music performances, somewhere around 5 cigarettes a day. but i cannot remember the exact amount. i have not smoked at all for two years or so.
Our daughter started having seizures at 3 weeks old, and was diagnosed with a severe genetic mutation (CDKL5 gene) during my paternity leave, which started when she was 3 months old.
I got pregnant at 4 months after giving birth to Maximus
I liked that I could take Paid Family Leave throughout his first year, as i took two weeks off at 3 different times thorugh out the year
I took off two weeks and worked partially from home. I work on salary and my boss didn't withhold any pay. I was paid fully for the 2 weeks. I then brought my child to work with me.

I was able to take off from work for his first year of life and I feel so grateful for that opportunity. The maternity/paternity leave is a joke. That was not the reason for me being able to take the time off.
It made a difference in balancing our relationship when it came to child care duties.

I work from home two days a week and from the office the other three. Although I did not receive paid leave from my employer he did let me work from home two-three extra weeks after my state disability expired.
Nothing
I took a total of 4.5 months after my daughter was born. It was very difficult returning to work, but at the same time I feel blessed to have had the time I did with her.
column534: Time varies. I often fall asleep on the couch between 10-11 and then to bed around 5AM
column536: Whenever the baby wakes up- between 6:45-7:30AM

column44:
My leave was for 7 weeks.  Though CA PFL would have covered up to 12 weeks (6 weeks disability and 6 weeks PFL), the circumstances of my job required me to return to work earlier (a suitable substitute teacher could not be found).

In addition, because my employer does not contribute to family leave, I was dependent on state leave, which was only about 50% of my paycheck.  A longer maternity leave would have put an insurmountable hardship on our finances.
I'm a stay at home dad, but I'm also an actor. I didn't try to get any jobs or auditions for the first year after she was born.

i took my initial 8 weeks off after birth and than i saved the last 4 months for the holidays. I am grateful that i did this because i was able to enjoy my son at a stage where he was learning to walk and really grow his personality.
column534: work has been a bit busy, so it has ranged from 9PM - 3AM.
column535: 5 to 20 minutes. depends on how many things are on my mind.

I was only able to take a week off. I was working contract and my employer let me know that my job was not guaranteed if I took an extended leave.
I did not take any time off work which I now regret.
